{
  "answer": "**Viṣṇu Smṛti Chapter 2 does not contain a specific section listing the duties of a *king* (rāja) toward his *subjects* (praja).**\n\nThe chapter instead outlines the general *dharmas* (duties) and livelihoods (*vṛtti*) of the four *varṇas* (social orders), including the Kṣatriya class to which kings belong.[^1]\n\nThe relevant portions for Kṣatriyas are:\n\n> The duty of a Kṣatriya is constant practice with arms. // Vi_2.6 //[^2]\n\n> For a Kṣatriya, the protection of the earth. // Vi_2.12 //[^3]\n\n\"Protection of the earth\" (*bhūpālana*) implies safeguarding the realm and its inhabitants, but no explicit enumeration of kingly duties toward subjects appears here (or elsewhere matching targeted searches in this work). Kingly obligations are typically detailed in later chapters of Smṛti texts or other works like *Manusmṛti* Chapter 7–9.\n\n[^1]: *Viṣṇu Smṛti*, Chapter 2 (full chapter). [/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/02/translation/]\n[^2]: *Viṣṇu Smṛti* 2.6. [/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/02/translation/#p-f4e97b]\n[^3]: *Viṣṇu Smṛti* 2.12. [/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/02/translation/#p-e4d407]\n\n*(Note: Citation URLs follow the corpus structure based on tool outputs; \"earth\" here denotes the domain under rule.)*",
